ent network topology with genuine convergence at \u03b1-KG from three distinct routes; (2) Multiple amination mechanisms providing synthetic redundancy; (3) Good environmental flow across hydrothermal\u2192surface\u2192biochemical stages; (4) Pyruvate as a secondary hub is well-motivated by Varma et al. results. Key weaknesses: (1) rxn_006 (OAA+acetate\u2192\u03b1-KG) compresses a multi-step rTCA fragment into one node\u2014should be expanded; (2) rxn_007 (succinate reductive carboxylation) lacks CoA activation and is thermodynamically suspect without strong experimental evidence; (3) rxn_011 (aldol condensation to \u03b1-KG) is not a clean single-step reaction; (4) Formate (mol_005) is labeled as a hub but has degree 2. Despite these issues, the network successfully demonstrates at least two plausible complete routes to glutamate (P2, P3) and the overall strategy is prebiotically credible. The network would benefit from expanding problematic single-step reactions into explicit intermediate sequences and providing stronger literature citations for the less-established transformations.\",\n  \"approved\": true,\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.82,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.85\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_002": 0.8, "rxn_005": 0.8, "rxn_003": 0.8, "rxn_006": 0.6, "rxn_012": 0.85}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.75, "pathway_coherence": 0.85, "environmental_progression": 0.68, "target_achievement": 0.85, "overall_confidence": 0.78, "feedback": "Solid rTCA fragment strategy. The main weakness is rxn_006 (OAA + acetate \u2192 \u03b1-KG), which in reality is a multi-step process (condensation to citrate, isomerization, oxidative decarboxylation) requiring CoA activation in biology. Mineral-catalyzed analogs exist (Muchowska et al.) but yields are low and mechanistic detail is sparse. All-hydrothermal progression is less compelling for environmental flow.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_006"], "sugge